3: ## Socket handling
4: 
5: Envoy uses the following procedure for creating sockets and assigning them to workers.
6: 
7: 1. When a listener is created, a socket is pre-created for every worker on the main thread. This
8:    allows most errors to be caught early on in the listener creation process (e.g., bad socket
9:    option, unable to bind, etc.).
10:     * If using reuse_port, a unique socket is created for every worker.
11:     * If not using reuse_port, a unique socket is created for worker 0, and then that socket
12:       is duplicated for all other workers.
13: 2. In the case of a listener update in which the address/socket is to be shared (i.e., a named
14:    listener that has configuration settings changed but listens on the same address will share
15:    sockets with the draining listener), all sockets are duplicated regardless of whether using
16:    reuse_port or not. This keeps the logic equivalent, and also makes sure that when using
17: ","endLine":17,"startLine":2},{"content":"17:    reuse_port no TCP connections are dropped during the drain process (in the race condition between
18:    assigning a queue and closing the listening socket on the old listener).
19: 3. In the case of hot restart, all sockets are requested by worker index. If the old process has
20:    a match, the socket is duplicated and sent to the new process. Thus, hot restart and a listener
21:    update effectively share the same update process. This is so that no connections are dropped
22: ","endLine":22,"startLine":17},{"content":"22:    when using reuse_port.
23: 4. A consequence of every listener having dedicated sockets (whether duplicated or not) is that
24:    a listener can close() its sockets when removed without concern for other listeners.
25: 
26: For more information, see `ListenSocketFactoryImpl` and its use within `ListenerImpl` and
27: `ListenerManagerImpl`.
